Why biostatisticians learn to program

  • Jobs: Industry, academic, collaboration…
    • Google’s Chief Economist: “I keep saying that the sexy job in the next 10 years will be statisticians. And I’m not kidding.”
  • Data analysis:
    • Independence: You don’t rely on someone else giving you exactly the right tool.
    • Honesty: You don’t distort your problem to match the tools you have.
    • Clarity: You can turn your ideas into something a machine can do refines your thinking.
  • Fun: You can apply cool tools to convert data into knowledge.

What software do we need?

  • R is a programming language for statistical computing
  • R Studio is an integrated development environment for R programming
  • R Markdown is a markup language for combining R code with text

All 3 are free, and all 3 will be used extensively in this course

(survey, demo)

Installing R

  • All R materials are download from the ``Comprehensive R Archive Network" (CRAN), which is a collection of sites from around the world carrying identical and current R code and documentation.
  • R can be installed on Windows, Mac or Linux operating systems.
  • In this course, the instructors will run R on Mac.
  • To install R, visit the R website, http://www.r-project.org and follow the installation directions (see the FAQ section for more details).

R Console

  • When you first open R, you will see the R window. The console is the fundamental way for interacting with R.
  • In the console is a prompt, > this is where an expression, phrase of code that can be executed, is inputed into R (if entering lengthy expressions that require more than one line the prompt changes from > to +.
  • An expression is typed into the console at the prompt, press Enter, and the expression is evaluated.
  • Depending on the expression, the system may respond by outputting results to the console, creating a graph in a new window or performing some other task. Then another expression can be inputed and evaluated.
  • An R session is this interaction between you and the system.
  • Often included with outputted results in the console are numbers in [ ]. These numbers are used to reference locations in the output.

RStudio

  • RStudio is a free and open source integrated development environment (IDE) designed specifically for R. http://www.rstudio.com
  • Runs on, Windows, Mac or Linux operating systems.
  • Useful productivity tools：
    • Syntax highlighting, smart indention, parentheses matching
    • Easily execute code from the source editor
    • Integrates all of the tools (source editor, console, plots, documentation, and more) when working with R into a single environment
    • Extensive tools for developing R packages
    • Interactive debugging for diagnosing and fixing errors

Why we should learn R

  • It’s free, open source, and available on every major platform.
  • A massive set of packges for statistical modeling, machine learning, visualization and importing and manipulating data.
  • Cutting edge tools.
  • A fantastic community.
  • Powerful tools for communicating your results. (html, pdf, interactive website).
  • An IDE (RStudio).
  • Connect to high-performance programming languages (C, C++, Java)
  • When you published a statistical methodology paper, often you will be asked to publish a R package as well.

Some drawbacks of R

  • R is not a particularly fast programming language, and poorly written R code can be terribly slow. R is also a profligate user of memory.
  • R language focuses on results instead of processes. Too many R functions use tricks to reduce the amount of typing at the cost of making code hard to understand.
  • R is slow in loop (e.g. for, while) so try to avoid loop in R if you run a large program and care about speed.
